  m_text: "Banana trees are large, fast-growing tropical plants that are technically
    giant herbs rather than true trees, as they lack a woody trunk. Instead, they
    have a \u201Cpseudostem\u201D formed by tightly packed leaf bases, which can
    reach heights of 10 to 30 feet depending on the variety. Their broad, bright
    green leaves can grow several feet long and are easily torn by wind, giving the
    plant a distinctive fringed appearance. Banana plants thrive in warm, humid climates
    with plenty of sunlight and water, and they produce clusters of fruit known as
    hands, which together form a bunch. After fruiting, the main stem dies back,
    but new shoots, called suckers, emerge from the base to continue the plant\u2019s
    life cycle."
